        | Quantum computing is a promising emerging technology, but its counterintuitive rules make it difficult to design and implement quantum algorithms. In the classical setting, the programmer can rely on automated verification techniques, in order to prove that an algorithm is correct and satisfies the desired requirements. The classical techniques, however, suffer from exponential computational cost when applied to the quantum setting. We will review some of the proposed approaches and their shortcomings, and discuss some possible future paths.
